{"title_page": "China Coast Guard", "text_new": "{{short description|Coast guard of China}}\n{{About|Coast guard of the People's Republic of China|the coast guard of the Republic of China|Coast Guard Administration (Taiwan)}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name = Chinese People's Armed Police Force <br> Coast Guard Corps <br> (China Coast Guard Bureau) <br />\u4e2d\u56fd\u4eba\u6c11\u6b66\u88c5\u8b66\u5bdf\u90e8\u961f\u6d77\u8b66\u603b\u961f\uff08\u4e2d\u56fd\u6d77\u8b66\u5c40\uff09<br />\n| image = [[File:Emblem of China Coast Guard.svg|150px]]\n| caption = Emblem of China Coast Guard\n| dates = July 2013 ~ Mar 2018 <br> Mar 2018 ~ (Reorganisation)\n| country = {{Flag|China}}\n| allegiance = {{Flagicon image| Flag of the Chinese Communist Party.svg}} [[Communist Party of China]]<!--Because under control of Central Military Commission ultimately-->\n| branch = \n| type = [[Coast Guard]]\n| role = [[Coastal defence and fortification|Coastal defense]], [[Admiralty law|maritime law enforcement]], [[search and rescue]]\n| size = 16,296 personnel (~2018)\n| command_structure = {{Flagicon image|People's Armed Police Flag.svg|size=25px}} [[People's Armed Police]]<br>(2018&ndash;)<br />{{Flagicon image|State Oceanic Administration of P.R.China badge.svg|size=25px}} [[State Oceanic Administration]]<br>(2013&ndash;2018)<br />{{Flagicon image|Police Badge,P.R.China.svg|size=25px}} [[People's Armed Police|PAP]] Border Security Force<br><small>(under the [[Ministry of Public Security (China)|Ministry of Public Security]])</small><br>(until 2013)\n| garrison = \n| garrison_label = Headquarters\n| nickname = \n| motto = \n| patron = \n| colors = {{colour box|#0000FF}}{{colour box|#FFFFFF}}{{colour box|#FF0000}} Blue, White, Red\n| colors_label = Colours\n| march = \n| mascot = \n| equipment = 164 [[Cutter (boat)|cutters]]<br /> Multiple [[patrol boat]]s (2018)\n| equipment_label = Fleet\n| battles = \n| anniversaries = \n| decorations = \n| battle_honours = <!-- Commanders -->\n| website = \n| commander1 = PAP [[Major General|Maj Gen]] Wang Zhongcai <ref>[http://www.mohrss.gov.cn/SYrlzyhshbzb/sydqjdxs/SYguowuyuanrenmian/201712/t20171208_283535.html Deployment arrangement from State Council of the People's Republic of China]</ref>\n| commander1_label = Director\n| commander2 = PAP [[Major General|Maj Gen]] Wang Liangfu\n| commander2_label = [[Political commissar]]\n| commander3 = \n| commander3_label = \n| notable_commanders = <!-- Insignia -->\n| identification_symbol = [[File:Flag of the People's Republic of China.svg|150px]]\n| identification_symbol_label = Flag\n| identification_symbol_2 = [[File:China Coast Guard racing stripe.svg|150px]]\n| identification_symbol_2_label = Racing stripe\n| identification_symbol_3 = \n| identification_symbol_3_label = \n| identification_symbol_4 = \n| identification_symbol_4_label = <!-- Aircraft -->\n| aircraft_attack = \n| aircraft_bomber = \n| aircraft_electronic = \n| aircraft_fighter = \n| aircraft_helicopter = [[Harbin Z-9]]\n| aircraft_interceptor = \n| aircraft_patrol = [[Harbin Y-12]]\n| aircraft_recon = \n| aircraft_trainer = \n| aircraft_transport = \n}}\n[[File:CHINA COAST GUARD badge.svg|thumb|200px|Badge of China Coast Guard before 2013, when part of the PAP Border Security Force under the [[Ministry of Public Security (China)|Ministry of Public Security]].]]\n{{Politics of China |expanded = Military }}\n\nThe '''Chinese People's Armed Police Force Coast Guard Corps''' ({{zh |s = \u4e2d\u56fd\u4eba\u6c11\u6b66\u88c5\u8b66\u5bdf\u90e8\u961f\u6d77\u8b66\u603b\u961f |p = Zh\u014dnggu\u00f3 R\u00e9nm\u00edn W\u01d4zhu\u0101ng J\u01d0ngch\u00e1 B\u00f9du\u00ec H\u01ceij\u01d0ng Z\u01d2ngdu\u00ec }}), also called '''China Coast Guard Bureau ''' ({{zh |s = \u4e2d\u56fd\u6d77\u8b66\u5c40 |p = Zh\u014dnggu\u00f3 H\u01ceij\u012dng J\u00fa | l = China Maritime Police Bureau  }}) and abbreviated as '''China Coast Guard''' ({{zh |s = \u4e2d\u56fd\u6d77\u8b66 |p = Zh\u014dnggu\u00f3 H\u01ceij\u012dng |l = China Maritime Police }}) or '''Haijing''' ({{zh |s = \u6d77\u8b66 |p = H\u01ceij\u012dng |l = Maritime Police }}) serves as a coordinating agency for maritime [[search and rescue]] and [[Admiralty law|law enforcement]] in the [[territorial waters]] of the [[People's Republic of China]]. It is currently the world's largest [[coast guard]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Erickson |first1=Andrew S. |title=Numbers Matter: China's Three 'Navies' Each Have the World's Most Ships |url=http://nationalinterest.org/feature/numbers-matter-chinas-three-navies-each-have-the-worlds-most-24653 |work=The National Interest |date=26 February 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=China\u2019s Three \u2018Navies\u2019 Each Have the World\u2019s Most Ships |url=https://warisboring.com/chinas-three-navies-each-have-the-worlds-most-ships/}}</ref>\n\nThe China Coast Guard was formerly the maritime branch of the [[People's Armed Police]] (PAP) Border Security Force under the [[Ministry of Public Security (China)|Ministry of Public Security]] until 2013. In March 2013, China announced it would form a unified Coast Guard commanded by the [[State Oceanic Administration]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2013npc/2013-03/11/content_16296448.htm |title = Nation merging maritime patrol forces - Latest News |author = \u5173\u6653\u840c |website = www.chinadaily.com.cn }}</ref> The new Coast Guard has been in operation since July 2013.<ref>http://www.defensenews.com/article/20130723/DEFREG03/307230021/China-Unveils-Coast-Guard-Handle-Sea-Conflict</ref> As of July 1, 2018, the China Coast Guard was transferred from civilian control of the [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|State Council]] and the [[State Oceanic Administration]], to the [[People's Armed Police]], ultimately placing it under the command of the [[Central Military Commission (China)|Central Military Commission]].<ref>[https://www3.nhk.or.jp/nhkworld/en/news/20180322_11/ \u2013 Articles \u2013 China's coast guard to be under military police] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180322142847/https://www3.nhk.or.jp/nhkworld/en/news/20180322_11/ |date=2018-03-22 }} NHK World, March 22nd 2018</ref><ref>{{cite news |publisher=[[Jane's Information Group]] |url=http://www.janes.com/article/81341/control-over-china-coast-guard-to-be-transferred-to-cmc?from_rss=1 |title=Control over China Coast Guard to be transferred to CMC |first=Andrew |last=Tate |date=June 26, 2018 |quote=Legislation passed by the National People\u2019s Congress (NPC) on 22 June will implement changes announced in March that the CCG will come under the control of the People\u2019s Armed Police Force (PAPF) and, ultimately, the command of China\u2019s Central Military Commission (CMC).}}</ref>\n\nThe formal name of the organization is \"Chinese People's Armed Police Force Coast Guard Corps\" (PAPCGC), but \"China Coast Guard Bureau/China Coast Guard\" (CCGB/CCG) is retained for general use.\n\n== Function ==\nThe CCG is known to perform mostly coastal and oceanic search and rescue or patrols, including anti-smuggling operations. During wartime it may be placed under the operational control of the [[People's Liberation Army Navy]].\n\n=== Roles ===\nRoles of the CCG are diverse but include:\n* Patrol of territorial waters and disputed territories\n* Anti-smuggling, anti-piracy\n* Maritime policing and ship inspections\n* Harbour and coastal security\n* Research and survey\n* Search and Rescue\n* Fisheries protection\nIn June 2018, the China Coast Guard was granted maritime rights and law enforcement akin civilian law enforcement agencies in order to carry out contrast of illegal activities, keep peace and order, as well as safeguarding security at sea, when performing duties related to the use of marine resources, protection of marine environment, regulation of fishery, and anti-smuggling.<ref name=\"NPCObs22Jun18\">{{cite news |last1=Wei |first1=Changhao |title=NPCSC Defers Vote on E-Commerce Law, Grants Law Enforcement Powers to Military-Controlled Coast Guard |url=https://npcobserver.com/2018/06/22/npcsc-defers-vote-on-e-commerce-law-grants-law-enforcement-powers-to-military-controlled-coast-guard/ |accessdate=16 October 2019 |work=NPC Observer |date=22 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Command ===\nAfter the reform in 2018, CCG consists commands (subbureaus) and divisions (local bureaus). The name in the parentheses is for general use.\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=35em|\n* People's Armed Police Coast Guard Crops East China Sea Command (China Coast Guard East China Sea Subbureau) \n** Jiangsu Division (Jiangsu Coast Guard Bureau)\n** Shanghai Division (Shanghai CGB)\n** Zhejiang Division (Zhejiang CGB)\n** Fujian Division (Fujian CGB)\n** 1st Division (1st Direct Breau)\n** 2nd Division (2nd DB)\n** 1st Wing\n*  PAPCGC South China Sea Command (CCG South China Sea Subbureau) \n** Guangdong Division (Guangdong CGB)\n** Guangxi Division (Guangxi CGB)\n** Hainan Division (Hainan CGB)\n** 3rd Division (3rd DB)\n** 4th Division (4th DB)\n** 5th Division (5th DB)\n** 2nd Wing\n* PAPCGC North China Sea Command (CCG North China Sea Subbureau) \n** Liaoning Division (Liaoning CGB)\n** Tianjing Division (Tianjing CGB)\n** Hebei Division (Hebei CGB)\n** Shandong Division (Shandong CGB)\n** 6th Division (6th DB)\n** 3rd Wing\n}}\n\n=== Training ===\nThe Chinese Coast Guard conducts periodic joint-training sessions with other navies, including the US Coast Guard service.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.uscgpacificarea.com/go/doc/833/120364/|title=Logon Form<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=}}</ref>  The Chinese Coast Guard also participates in the annual [[North Pacific Coast Guard Agencies Forum]] in Alaska, along with US, Canadian, Japanese, South Korean, and Russian Coast Guards.  As part of an exchange program, members of the Chinese Coast Guard service have been assigned to serve on [[United States Coast Guard|U.S. Coast Guard]] cutters.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.realclearpolitics.com/articles/2006/12/china_and_the_us_coast_guard.html |title = RealClearPolitics - Articles - U.S. Coast Guard Has Chinese aboard |website = www.realclearpolitics.com }}</ref>\n\n== Equipment ==\n{{Main|Equipment of the China Coast Guard}}\n\n=== Vessels ===\n[[File:Joint Rescue Exercise 120906-G-ZQ587-004.jpg|thumb|The crew of the U.S. Coast Guard Cutter Galveston Island (background), is underway alongside the crew of the People's Republic of China Maritime Safety Administration ship Haixun 31 (foreground) eight miles offshore of Honolulu, Sept. 6, 2012.]]\n\nChinese Coast Guard ships are painted white with blue stripe and wording China Coast Guard in English and Chinese.\n\nTypical Coast Guard ships include the 130 ton [[Type 218 patrol boat]] (100 boats), armed with twin 14.5mm machine guns, assorted speedboats, and few larger patrol ships.  Up until very recently, the largest ship in Chinese Coast Guard service was the 1,500 ton [[Haixun-class cutter|Type 718 cutter]] (31101 Pudong).\n\nIn March 2007, it was reported that the [[People's Liberation Army Navy|PLAN]] had transferred 2 [[Type 053 frigate|Type 728 cutter]] (44102, ex-509 Changde; 46103, ex-510 Shaoxing) to the Coast Guard and re-numbered them as 1002 & 1003.  At the time these ships were the largest vessels in the China Coast Guard inventory.\n\nIn May 2017, it was reported that China had deployed the 12,000 ton China Coast Guard (CCG) 3901 cutter No. 1123 to patrol its claimed islands in the disputed South China Sea.<ref name=\"monster\">{{cite web |url = http://nationalinterest.org/blog/the-buzz/china-sent-monster-ship-roam-the-south-china-sea-20608 |title = China Sent A 'Monster' Ship To Roam The South China Sea |publisher=The National Interest |author=Ryan Pickrell |date =  2017-05-11 |accessdate= 2018-02-02 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.scsb.gov.cn/scsb/tpxw/201705/e97e36f19ea047a9a462d7be295e7196.shtml |title = \u5357\u6d77\u533a2017\u5e74\u5ea6\u897f\u6c99\u6d77\u57df\u6d77\u5c9b\u4fdd\u62a4\u8054\u5408\u6267\u6cd5\u884c\u52a8\u5706\u6ee1\u5b8c\u6210 |publisher=South China Sea Branch, State Oceanic Administration |date = 2017-05-04 |accessdate = 2018-02-02 }}</ref> The CCG 3901 cutter is the world's biggest coast guard cutter, and is much larger than the U.S. Navy's 9,800 ton [[Ticonderoga-class_cruiser|''Ticonderoga''-class]] guided-missile cruisers and its 8,300-9,300 ton [[Arleigh_Burke-class_destroyer|''Arleigh Burke''-class]] guided missile destroyers.<ref name=biggest>{{cite web |url =  http://www.chinatopix.com/articles/114102/20170512/china-coast-guard-peoples-liberation-army-ccg-3901-cutter-south-china-sea |title = China Deploys World's Biggest Coast Guard Cutter CCG 3901 to Patrol South China Sea |publisher=China Topix |author = Charissa Echavez |date = 2017-05-12 |accessdate = 2018-02-02 }}</ref> The CCG 3901 cutter is armed with 76mm H/PJ-26 rapid fire naval guns, two auxiliary guns, and two anti-aircraft guns.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100811202448/http://www.sinodefence.com/navy/coastguard/default.asp CCG \u2013 Chinese Defence Today]\n* {{in lang|zh}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20080228215025/http://www.msa.gov.cn/ China Maritime Safety Administration official website]\n* {{in lang|zh}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20141220040501/http://www.soa.gov.cn/ China State Oceanic Administration]\n* {{in lang|zh}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20080209230415/http://www.aton.gov.cn/ Aid to navigation]\n* {{in lang|zh}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20070228032714/http://www.hydro.gov.cn/cheng/module/default.aspx China Hydrography]\n* {{in lang|zh}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20110707051136/http://www.sinoras.cn/ China Rescue & Salvage]\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|China|Transport}}\n* [[Republic of China Coast Guard]]\n* [[People's Armed Police]]\n* [[People's Liberation Army Navy]]\n** [[People's Liberation Army Navy Coastal Defense Force]]\n* [[China Maritime Safety Administration]] takes on the navigation safety and control duties, including harbormaster powers in most ports. It was not merged with the new coast guard in 2013.\n* [[China Marine Surveillance]] Defunct in July 2013. The present China Coast Guard is a unified force that conducts law-enforcement operations in waters administered by China.\n\n{{-}}\n{{Geographic location\n|North = [[Republic of Korea Coast Guard]]\n|Northeast = [[Japan Coast Guard]]\n|East = [[Republic of China Coast Guard]]\n|West = [[Mainland China]]\n|Centre = China Coast Guard\n|South = [[Vietnam People's Coast Guard]]\n|Southeast = [[Philippine Coast Guard]]\n}}\n\n{{Coast guards}}\n{{China national security}}\n{{People's Liberation Army}}\n\n[[Category:China Coast Guard| ]]\n[[Category:Military of the People's Republic of China]]\n[[Category:People's Armed Police]]\n[[Category:Reserve forces]]\n[[Category:Law enforcement agencies of China]]\n[[Category:Auxiliary military units]]\n[[Category:Coast guards]]\n[[Category:State Oceanic Administration]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Coast guard of China}}\n{{About|Coast guard of the People's Republic of China|the coast guard of the Republic of China|Coast Guard Administration (Taiwan)}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n| unit_name = Chinese People's Armed Police Force <br> Coast Guard Corps <br> (China Coast Guard Bureau) <br />\u4e2d\u56fd\u4eba\u6c11\u6b66\u88c5\u8b66\u5bdf\u90e8\u961f\u6d77\u8b66\u603b\u961f\uff08\u4e2d\u56fd\u6d77\u8b66\u5c40\uff09<br />\n| image = [[File:Emblem of China Coast Guard.svg|150px]]\n| caption = Emblem of China Coast Guard\n| dates = July 2013 ~ Mar 2018 <br> Mar 2018 ~ (Reorganisation)\n| country = {{Flag|China}}\n| allegiance = {{Flagicon image| Flag of the Chinese Communist Party.svg}} [[Communist Party of China]]<!--Because under control of Central Military Commission ultimately-->\n| branch = \n| type = [[Coast Guard]]\n| role = [[Coastal defence and fortification|Coastal defense]], [[Admiralty law|maritime law enforcement]], [[search and rescue]]\n| size = 16,296 personnel (~2018)\n| command_structure = {{Flagicon image|People's Armed Police Flag.svg|size=25px}} [[People's Armed Police]]<br>(2018&ndash;)<br />{{Flagicon image|State Oceanic Administration of P.R.China badge.svg|size=25px}} [[State Oceanic Administration]]<br>(2013&ndash;2018)<br />{{Flagicon image|Police Badge,P.R.China.svg|size=25px}} [[People's Armed Police|PAP]] Border Security Force<br><small>(under the [[Ministry of Public Security (China)|Ministry of Public Security]])</small><br>(until 2013)\n| garrison = \n| garrison_label = Headquarters\n| nickname = \n| motto = \n| patron = \n| colors = {{colour box|#0000FF}}{{colour box|#FFFFFF}}{{colour box|#FF0000}} Blue, White, Red\n| colors_label = Colours\n| march = \n| mascot = \n| equipment = 164 [[Cutter (boat)|cutters]]<br /> Multiple [[patrol boat]]s (2018)\n| equipment_label = Fleet\n| battles = \n| anniversaries = \n| decorations = \n| battle_honours = <!-- Commanders -->\n| website = \n| commander1 = PAP [[Major General|Maj Gen]] Wang Zhongcai <ref>[http://www.mohrss.gov.cn/SYrlzyhshbzb/sydqjdxs/SYguowuyuanrenmian/201712/t20171208_283535.html Deployment arrangement from State Council of the People's Republic of China]</ref>\n| commander1_label = Director\n| commander2 = PAP [[Major General|Maj Gen]] Wang Liangfu\n| commander2_label = [[Political commissar]]\n| commander3 = \n| commander3_label = \n| notable_commanders = <!-- Insignia -->\n| identification_symbol = [[File:Flag of the People's Republic of China.svg|150px]]\n| identification_symbol_label = Flag\n| identification_symbol_2 = [[File:China Coast Guard racing stripe.svg|150px]]\n| identification_symbol_2_label = Racing stripe\n| identification_symbol_3 = \n| identification_symbol_3_label = \n| identification_symbol_4 = \n| identification_symbol_4_label = <!-- Aircraft -->\n| aircraft_attack = \n| aircraft_bomber = \n| aircraft_electronic = \n| aircraft_fighter = \n| aircraft_helicopter = [[Harbin Z-9]]\n| aircraft_interceptor = \n| aircraft_patrol = [[Harbin Y-12]]\n| aircraft_recon = \n| aircraft_trainer = \n| aircraft_transport = \n}}\n[[File:CHINA COAST GUARD badge.svg|thumb|200px|Badge of China Coast Guard before 2013, when part of the PAP Border Security Force under the [[Ministry of Public Security (China)|Ministry of Public Security]].]]\n{{Politics of China |expanded = Military }}\n\nThe '''Chinese People's Armed Police Force Coast Guard Corps''' ({{zh |s = \u4e2d\u56fd\u4eba\u6c11\u6b66\u88c5\u8b66\u5bdf\u90e8\u961f\u6d77\u8b66\u603b\u961f |p = Zh\u014dnggu\u00f3 R\u00e9nm\u00edn W\u01d4zhu\u0101ng J\u01d0ngch\u00e1 B\u00f9du\u00ec H\u01ceij\u01d0ng Z\u01d2ngdu\u00ec }}), also called '''China Coast Guard Bureau ''' ({{zh |s = \u4e2d\u56fd\u6d77\u8b66\u5c40 |p = Zh\u014dnggu\u00f3 H\u01ceij\u012dng J\u00fa | l = China Maritime Police Bureau  }}) and abbreviated as '''China Coast Guard''' ({{zh |s = \u4e2d\u56fd\u6d77\u8b66 |p = Zh\u014dnggu\u00f3 H\u01ceij\u012dng |l = China Maritime Police }}) or '''Haijing''' ({{zh |s = \u6d77\u8b66 |p = H\u01ceij\u012dng |l = Maritime Police }}) serves as a coordinating agency for maritime [[search and rescue]] and [[Admiralty law|law enforcement]] in the [[territorial waters]] of the [[People's Republic of China]]. It is currently the world's largest [[coast guard]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Erickson |first1=Andrew S. |title=Numbers Matter: China's Three 'Navies' Each Have the World's Most Ships |url=http://nationalinterest.org/feature/numbers-matter-chinas-three-navies-each-have-the-worlds-most-24653 |work=The National Interest |date=26 February 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=China\u2019s Three \u2018Navies\u2019 Each Have the World\u2019s Most Ships |url=https://warisboring.com/chinas-three-navies-each-have-the-worlds-most-ships/}}</ref>\n\nThe China Coast Guard was formerly the maritime branch of the [[People's Armed Police]] (PAP) Border Security Force under the [[Ministry of Public Security (China)|Ministry of Public Security]] until 2013. In March 2013, China announced it would form a unified Coast Guard commanded by the [[State Oceanic Administration]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/china/2013npc/2013-03/11/content_16296448.htm |title = Nation merging maritime patrol forces - Latest News |author = \u5173\u6653\u840c |website = www.chinadaily.com.cn }}</ref> The new Coast Guard has been in operation since July 2013.<ref>http://www.defensenews.com/article/20130723/DEFREG03/307230021/China-Unveils-Coast-Guard-Handle-Sea-Conflict</ref> As of July 1, 2018, the China Coast Guard was transferred from civilian control of the [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|State Council]] and the [[State Oceanic Administration]], to the [[People's Armed Police]], ultimately placing it under the command of the [[Central Military Commission (China)|Central Military Commission]].<ref>[https://www3.nhk.or.jp/nhkworld/en/news/20180322_11/ \u2013 Articles \u2013 China's coast guard to be under military police] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180322142847/https://www3.nhk.or.jp/nhkworld/en/news/20180322_11/ |date=2018-03-22 }} NHK World, March 22nd 2018</ref><ref>{{cite news |publisher=[[Jane's Information Group]] |url=http://www.janes.com/article/81341/control-over-china-coast-guard-to-be-transferred-to-cmc?from_rss=1 |title=Control over China Coast Guard to be transferred to CMC |first=Andrew |last=Tate |date=June 26, 2018 |quote=Legislation passed by the National People\u2019s Congress (NPC) on 22 June will implement changes announced in March that the CCG will come under the control of the People\u2019s Armed Police Force (PAPF) and, ultimately, the command of China\u2019s Central Military Commission (CMC).}}</ref>\n\nThe formal name of the organization is \"Chinese People's Armed Police Force Coast Guard Corps\" (PAPCGC), but \"China Coast Guard Bureau/China Coast Guard\" (CCGB/CCG) is retained for general use.\n\n== Function ==\nThe CCG is known to perform mostly coastal and oceanic search and rescue or patrols, including anti-smuggling operations. During wartime it may be placed under the operational control of the [[People's Liberation Army Navy]].\n\n=== Roles ===\nRoles of the CCG are diverse but include:\n* Patrol of territorial waters and disputed territories\n* Anti-smuggling, anti-piracy\n* Maritime policing and ship inspections\n* Harbour and coastal security\n* Research and survey\n* Search and Rescue\n* Fisheries protection\nIn June 2018, the China Coast Guard was granted maritime rights and law enforcement akin civilian law enforcement agencies in order to carry out contrast of illegal activities, keep peace and order, as well as safeguarding security at sea, when performing duties related to the use of marine resources, protection of marine environment, regulation of fishery, and anti-smuggling.<ref name=\"NPCObs22Jun18\">{{cite news |last1=Wei |first1=Changhao |title=NPCSC Defers Vote on E-Commerce Law, Grants Law Enforcement Powers to Military-Controlled Coast Guard |url=https://npcobserver.com/2018/06/22/npcsc-defers-vote-on-e-commerce-law-grants-law-enforcement-powers-to-military-controlled-coast-guard/ |accessdate=16 October 2019 |work=NPC Observer |date=22 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Command ===\nAfter the reform in 2018, CCG consists commands (subbureaus) and divisions (local bureaus). The name in the parentheses is for general use.\n\n{{columns-list|colwidth=35em|\n* People's Armed Police Coast Guard Crops East China Sea Command (China Coast Guard East China Sea Subbureau) \n** Jiangsu Division (Jiangsu Coast Guard Bureau)\n** Shanghai Division (Shanghai CGB)\n** Zhejiang Division (Zhejiang CGB)\n** Fujian Division (Fujian CGB)\n** 1st Division (1st Direct Breau)\n** 2nd Division (2nd DB)\n** 1st Wing\n*  PAPCGC South China Sea Command (CCG South China Sea Subbureau) \n** Guangdong Division (Guangdong CGB)\n** Guangxi Division (Guangxi CGB)\n** Hainan Division (Hainan CGB)\n** 3rd Division (3rd DB)\n** 4th Division (4th DB)\n** 5th Division (5th DB)\n** 2nd Wing\n* PAPCGC North China Sea Command (CCG North China Sea Subbureau) \n** Liaoning Division (Liaoning CGB)\n** Tianjing Division (Tianjing CGB)\n** Hebei Division (Hebei CGB)\n** Shandong Division (Shandong CGB)\n** 6th Division (6th DB)\n** 3rd Wing\n}}\n\n=== Training ===\nThe Chinese Coast Guard conducts periodic joint-training sessions with other navies, including the US Coast Guard service.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.uscgpacificarea.com/go/doc/833/120364/|title=Logon Form<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=}}</ref>  The Chinese Coast Guard also participates in the annual [[North Pacific Coast Guard Agencies Forum]] in Alaska, along with US, Canadian, Japanese, South Korean, and Russian Coast Guards.  As part of an exchange program, members of the Chinese Coast Guard service have been assigned to serve on [[United States Coast Guard|U.S. Coast Guard]] cutters.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.realclearpolitics.com/articles/2006/12/china_and_the_us_coast_guard.html |title = RealClearPolitics - Articles - U.S. Coast Guard Has Chinese aboard |website = www.realclearpolitics.com }}</ref>\n\n== Equipment ==\n{{Main|Equipment of the China Coast Guard}}\n\n=== Vessels ===\n[[File:120906-G-ZQ587-004-Joint Rescue Exercise.jpg|thumb|The crew of the U.S. Coast Guard Cutter Galveston Island (background), is underway alongside the crew of the People's Republic of China Maritime Safety Administration ship Haixun 31 (foreground) eight miles offshore of Honolulu, Sept. 6, 2012.]]\n\nChinese Coast Guard ships are painted white with blue stripe and wording China Coast Guard in English and Chinese.\n\nTypical Coast Guard ships include the 130 ton [[Type 218 patrol boat]] (100 boats), armed with twin 14.5mm machine guns, assorted speedboats, and few larger patrol ships.  Up until very recently, the largest ship in Chinese Coast Guard service was the 1,500 ton [[Haixun-class cutter|Type 718 cutter]] (31101 Pudong).\n\nIn March 2007, it was reported that the [[People's Liberation Army Navy|PLAN]] had transferred 2 [[Type 053 frigate|Type 728 cutter]] (44102, ex-509 Changde; 46103, ex-510 Shaoxing) to the Coast Guard and re-numbered them as 1002 & 1003.  At the time these ships were the largest vessels in the China Coast Guard inventory.\n\nIn May 2017, it was reported that China had deployed the 12,000 ton China Coast Guard (CCG) 3901 cutter No. 1123 to patrol its claimed islands in the disputed South China Sea.<ref name=\"monster\">{{cite web |url = http://nationalinterest.org/blog/the-buzz/china-sent-monster-ship-roam-the-south-china-sea-20608 |title = China Sent A 'Monster' Ship To Roam The South China Sea |publisher=The National Interest |author=Ryan Pickrell |date =  2017-05-11 |accessdate= 2018-02-02 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.scsb.gov.cn/scsb/tpxw/201705/e97e36f19ea047a9a462d7be295e7196.shtml |title = \u5357\u6d77\u533a2017\u5e74\u5ea6\u897f\u6c99\u6d77\u57df\u6d77\u5c9b\u4fdd\u62a4\u8054\u5408\u6267\u6cd5\u884c\u52a8\u5706\u6ee1\u5b8c\u6210 |publisher=South China Sea Branch, State Oceanic Administration |date = 2017-05-04 |accessdate = 2018-02-02 }}</ref> The CCG 3901 cutter is the world's biggest coast guard cutter, and is much larger than the U.S. Navy's 9,800 ton [[Ticonderoga-class_cruiser|''Ticonderoga''-class]] guided-missile cruisers and its 8,300-9,300 ton [[Arleigh_Burke-class_destroyer|''Arleigh Burke''-class]] guided missile destroyers.<ref name=biggest>{{cite web |url =  http://www.chinatopix.com/articles/114102/20170512/china-coast-guard-peoples-liberation-army-ccg-3901-cutter-south-china-sea |title = China Deploys World's Biggest Coast Guard Cutter CCG 3901 to Patrol South China Sea |publisher=China Topix |author = Charissa Echavez |date = 2017-05-12 |accessdate = 2018-02-02 }}</ref> The CCG 3901 cutter is armed with 76mm H/PJ-26 rapid fire naval guns, two auxiliary guns, and two anti-aircraft guns.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100811202448/http://www.sinodefence.com/navy/coastguard/default.asp CCG \u2013 Chinese Defence Today]\n* {{in lang|zh}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20080228215025/http://www.msa.gov.cn/ China Maritime Safety Administration official website]\n* {{in lang|zh}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20141220040501/http://www.soa.gov.cn/ China State Oceanic Administration]\n* {{in lang|zh}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20080209230415/http://www.aton.gov.cn/ Aid to navigation]\n* {{in lang|zh}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20070228032714/http://www.hydro.gov.cn/cheng/module/default.aspx China Hydrography]\n* {{in lang|zh}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20110707051136/http://www.sinoras.cn/ China Rescue & Salvage]\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|China|Transport}}\n* [[Republic of China Coast Guard]]\n* [[People's Armed Police]]\n* [[People's Liberation Army Navy]]\n** [[People's Liberation Army Navy Coastal Defense Force]]\n* [[China Maritime Safety Administration]] takes on the navigation safety and control duties, including harbormaster powers in most ports. It was not merged with the new coast guard in 2013.\n* [[China Marine Surveillance]] Defunct in July 2013. The present China Coast Guard is a unified force that conducts law-enforcement operations in waters administered by China.\n\n{{-}}\n{{Geographic location\n|North = [[Republic of Korea Coast Guard]]\n|Northeast = [[Japan Coast Guard]]\n|East = [[Republic of China Coast Guard]]\n|West = [[Mainland China]]\n|Centre = China Coast Guard\n|South = [[Vietnam People's Coast Guard]]\n|Southeast = [[Philippine Coast Guard]]\n}}\n\n{{Coast guards}}\n{{China national security}}\n{{People's Liberation Army}}\n\n[[Category:China Coast Guard| ]]\n[[Category:Military of the People's Republic of China]]\n[[Category:People's Armed Police]]\n[[Category:Reserve forces]]\n[[Category:Law enforcement agencies of China]]\n[[