asjonene i Nord-Tr\u00f8ndelag |first=Gudbrand |last=\u00d8stbye  |authorlink=Gudbrand \u00d8stbye |year=1963 |publisher=Forsvarets Krigshistoriske Avdeling / Gyldendal |location=Oslo |language=Norwegian}}\n* {{cite book|title=Krigen i Norge 1940. Operasjonene til lands i Nord-Norge 1940 |volume=1 |first=Trygve |last=Sandvik |year=1965 |publisher=Forsvarets Krigshistoriske Avdeling / Gyldendal |location=Oslo |language=Norwegian}}\n* {{cite book|title=Krigen i Norge 1940. Operasjonene til lands i Nord-Norge 1940 |volume=2 |first=Trygve |last=Sandvik |year=1965 |publisher=Forsvarets Krigshistoriske Avdeling / Gyldendal |location=Oslo |language=Norwegian}}\n* {{cite book|last=Shirer |first=William L |authorlink=William L. Shirer |title=[[The Rise and Fall of the Third Reich|The Rise and Fall of the Third Reich: A History of Nazi Germany]] |publisher=Simon and Schuster|year=1990| isbn=0-671-72868-7 }}\n* {{cite book |title=Norsk historie 1939\u20131945: krig og okkupasjon |last=Skodvin |first=Magne |authorlink=Magne Skodvin |year=1991 |publisher=Samlaget |location=Oslo |isbn=82-521-3491-2 |page= |pages= |url=http://www.nb.no/utlevering/nb/358257b1c438e4197cf0f0307f5b20ea#&struct=DIV54 |language=Norwegian |accessdate=}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Weal |first=John |title=He 111 Kampfgeschwader in the West |year=2012 |publisher=Osprey Publishing |isbn=978-1-84908-670-7 |location=Oxford}}\n* {{cite book| last1=Wilkinson| first1=Peter| authorlink1=Peter Wilkinson (SOE)| last2=Astley| first2=Joan Bright| title=Gubbins and SOE| location=London| publisher=[[Pen And Sword Books|Leo Cooper]]| year=1993| isbn=0-85052-556-X}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Barnett, Correlli. ''Engage the Enemy More Closely: The Royal Navy in the Second World War'' (1991) pp 97\u2013139.\n* Butler,  J. R. M. ''History of Second World War: Grand strategy, volume 2: September 1939-June 1941'' (1957) pp 91\u2013150, [https://archive.org/details/grandstrategy02butl online free]\n* Elting, J.R. (1981) ''Battles for Scandinavia'', World War II Series, Alexandria, VA: Time-Life Books, {{ISBN|0-8094-3395-8}}\n* Kelly, Bernard.  \"Drifting Towards War: The British Chiefs of Staff, the USSR and the Winter War, November 1939\u2013March 1940,\" ''Contemporary British History,''  (2009)   23:3 pp 267\u2013291, DOI: 10.1080/13619460903080010\n*Kisely, John. 2017. ''Anatomy of a Campaign: The British Fiasco in Norway, 1940''. Cambridge University Press.\n* Mann, Chris; J\u00f6rgensen, Christer. ''Hitler's Arctic War: The German Campaigns in Norway, Finland & the USSR 1940\u201345'' (2002)\n* Plevy,  Harry. ''Norway 1940: Chronicle of a Chaotic Campaign'' (2017) [https://www.amazon.com/Norway-1940-Chronicle-Chaotic-Campaign/dp/1781555818 excerpt]\n* Ottmer, H.-M. (1994) ''Weser\u00fcbung: der deutsche Angriff auf D\u00e4nemark und Norwegen im April 1940'', Operationen des Zweiten Weltkrieges, '''1''', M\u00fcnchen : Oldenbourg, {{ISBN|3-486-56092-1}}\n* Roskill, S.W. ''The War at Sea, 1939-1945: The defensive. Vol. 1'' (HM Stationery Office, 1961), official history of Royal Navy, covers 1939-41\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Norwegian Campaign}}\n* [https://www.britishmilitaryhistory.co.uk/documents-france-norway-1940/ Campaign in Norway at www.BritishMilitaryHistory.co.uk]\n* [http://www.engdahl.oilgeopolitics.net/History/MacKinder/mackinder.html Halford Mackinder's Necessary War] An essay by [[F. William Engdahl]] describing the political manoeuvers behind the Norwegian Campaign\n* [http://digital.library.wisc.edu/1711.dl/FRUS.FRUS1940v01 United States Department of State Foreign relations of the United States diplomatic papers, 1940. General Volume I] p.&nbsp;136 onwards provides original documents which show how the conflict began.\n* [http://uboat.net/articles/?article=23 Torpedo Crisis of the U-Boats During Norwegian Campaign]\n\n{{World War II}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n\n[[Category:Norwegian Campaign| ]]\n[[Category:Amphibious operations involving Germany|Norwegian Campaign]]\n\n[[he:\u05d4\u05de\u05e2\u05e8\u05db\u05d4 \u05d1\u05e0\u05d5\u05e8\u05d1\u05d2\u05d9\u05d4]]\n", "name_user": "T\u00farelio", "label": "safe", "comment": "(GR)Duplicate:File:Germans in Oslo 9 April 1940.jpg\u2192File:German soldiers in Oslo 9 April 1940.jpgExact or scaled-down duplicate:c::File:German soldiers in Oslo 9 April 1940.jpg", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Norwegian_campaign"}
{"title_page": "Allan Gunn", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n\n'''Allan Gunn''' (23 November 1943 \u2013 2004) was an [[England|English]] former [[Football (soccer)|football]] [[Referee (association football)|referee]] in the [[The Football League|Football League]], [[Premier League]], and for [[FIFA]]. During his time on the List he was based in [[Sussex]], initially [[Burgess Hill]] and later [[Chailey]], near [[Lewes]].  Prior to officiating Gunn played as a left-winger for Sussex County League side [[Whitehawk F.C.|Whitehawk]].<ref>Sussex County Football League Programme, League Cup Semi-Final, Haywards Heath v Whitehawk, 31 March 1987</ref>\n\n==Career==\nGunn became a Football League [[Assistant referee (association football)|linesman]] in 1974 and two years later made the Supplementary Referees List. After a successful season at that level he was promoted to the full List in 1977.\n\nOver the next few years he made frequent appearances in the then [[Football League Division One]]. In 1986, he was senior linesman to [[Alan Robinson (referee)|Alan Robinson]] in the [[FA Cup Final 1986|FA Cup Final]] between [[Everton FC|Everton]] and [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]. He replaced the retiring Robinson on the FIFA list for the following season ([[1986-87 in English football|1986\u201387]]).\n\nHe took charge of an increasing number of key domestic games. In 1987, he refereed the [[Associate Members' Cup]] Final between [[Mansfield Town FC|Mansfield]] and [[Bristol City FC|Bristol City]]. This was the first professional English Cup Final to be settled by a [[Penalty shootout (football)|penalty shoot-out]]. Two years later, in April 1989, he handled the Final of the [[Full Members' Cup]] (a short-lived tournament for sides in the top two divisions) in which [[Nottingham Forest FC|Nottingham Forest]] overcame Everton 4\u20133. He was appointed to the [[FA Community Shield|Charity Shield]] a few months later. Many referees who have handled this game have shortly after graduated to the FA Cup Final{{citation needed|date=August 2007}} and he got his chance at the end of that season ([[1989-90 in English football|1989\u201390]]). The [[FA Cup Final 1990|Final]] between [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and [[Crystal Palace FC|Crystal Palace]] ended 3\u20133 after [[extra time]],<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=258975 FA Cup Final 1990]: [[soccerbase]].com website.</ref> and he also refereed the rather low-key replay, won by United 1\u20130.<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=258976 FA Cup Final Replay 1990]: soccerbase.com website.</ref>\n\nOn the international scene, he was referee for a number of club ties but his most notable match was a [[1990 FIFA World Cup qualification|World Cup qualifier]] in April 1989 in which [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] beat [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] 3\u20131.<ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/tablesz/zwit-intres-det.html Swiss international matches] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121101093724/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesz/zwit-intres-det.html |date=1 November 2012 }}, including the match against Portugal on 26 April 1989: ''RSSSF'' website.</ref>\n\nOriginally he was due to retire at the end of the [[1990-91 in English football|1990\u201391]] season. However, in common with a number of high-performing referees at that time, he was granted an extension. This gave him a few more months at FIFA level before the world body reduced its own retirement age to 45 and, along with many other referees, he had to stand down at the end of 1991. However, he continued to referee in England. He was chosen for the new [[Premier League]] in 1992, and in 1993 took charge of the [[1993 Football League Cup Final|League Cup Final]] between [[Arsenal FC|Arsenal]] and [[Sheffield Wednesday FC|Sheffield Wednesday]].<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=260059 Coca Cola Cup Final 1993]: soccerbase.com website.</ref>\n\nHe was then granted a further domestic extension. Early in 1994, though, he decided to retire at the end of the season at the age of 51, after a 17-year career on the full List. He accepted an offer from [[The Football Association|the FA]] in 2000 to become a member of the video panel reviewing match events and disciplinary matters.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/896175.stm \"Busy start for FA video panel\"], which included Allan Gunn from 2000: [[BBC.co.uk]] website article.</ref> He died in 2004.\n\n==References==\n\n===Print===\n{{refbegin}}\n*Football League Handbooks, 1974\u20131976\n*Rothmans Football Yearbooks, 1977\u20131994\n*Gilbert Upton (2005) Football League and Premiership Referees 1888 to 2005: a Reference Resource, Soccerdata\n{{refend}}\n\n===Internet===\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Soccerbase referee|6|A Gunn}}\n* [https://www.premierleague.com/referees/16871/overview Alan Gunn referee profile] at [[Premier League]]\n* {{WorldReferee.com|allan_gunn}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|title=[[FA Cup Final|FA&nbsp;Cup&nbsp;Final]]&nbsp;Referee|before=[[Joe Worrall (referee)|Joe Worrall]] |after=[[Roger Milford]] ||years=[[FA Cup Final 1990|1990]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gunn, Allan}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:People from Burgess Hill]]\n[[Category:Whitehawk F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English football referees]]\n[[Category:FA Cup Final referees]]\n[[Category:2004 deaths]]\n[[Category:English Football League referees]]\n[[Category:Premier League referees]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n'''Allan Gunn''' (23 November 1943 \u2013 2004) was an [[England|English]] former [[Football (soccer)|football]] [[Referee (association football)|referee]] in the [[The Football League|Football League]], [[Premier League]], and for [[FIFA]]. During his time on the List he was based in [[Sussex]], initially [[Burgess Hill]] and later [[Chailey]], near [[Lewes]].  Prior to officiating Gunn played as a left-winger for Sussex County League side [[Whitehawk F.C.|Whitehawk]].<ref>Sussex County Football League Programme, League Cup Semi-Final, Haywards Heath v Whitehawk, 31 March 1987</ref>\n\n==Career==\nGunn became a Football League [[Assistant referee (association football)|linesman]] in 1974 and two years later made the Supplementary Referees List. After a successful season at that level he was promoted to the full List in 1977.\n\nOver the next few years he made frequent appearances in the then [[Football League Division One]]. In 1986, he was senior linesman to [[Alan Robinson (referee)|Alan Robinson]] in the [[FA Cup Final 1986|FA Cup Final]] between [[Everton FC|Everton]] and [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]. He replaced the retiring Robinson on the FIFA list for the following season ([[1986-87 in English football|1986\u201387]]).\n\nHe took charge of an increasing number of key domestic games. In 1987, he refereed the [[Associate Members' Cup]] Final between [[Mansfield Town FC|Mansfield]] and [[Bristol City FC|Bristol City]]. This was the first professional English Cup Final to be settled by a [[Penalty shootout (football)|penalty shoot-out]]. Two years later, in April 1989, he handled the Final of the [[Full Members' Cup]] (a short-lived tournament for sides in the top two divisions) in which [[Nottingham Forest FC|Nottingham Forest]] overcame Everton 4\u20133. He was appointed to the [[FA Community Shield|Charity Shield]] a few months later. Many referees who have handled this game have shortly after graduated to the FA Cup Final{{citation needed|date=August 2007}} and he got his chance at the end of that season ([[1989-90 in English football|1989\u201390]]). The [[FA Cup Final 1990|Final]] between [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and [[Crystal Palace FC|Crystal Palace]] ended 3\u20133 after [[extra time]],<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=258975 FA Cup Final 1990]: [[soccerbase]].com website.</ref> and he also refereed the rather low-key replay, won by United 1\u20130.<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=258976 FA Cup Final Replay 1990]: soccerbase.com website.</ref>\n\nOn the international scene, he was referee for a number of club ties but his most notable match was a [[1990 FIFA World Cup qualification|World Cup qualifier]] in April 1989 in which [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] beat [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] 3\u20131.<ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/tablesz/zwit-intres-det.html Swiss international matches] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121101093724/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesz/zwit-intres-det.html |date=1 November 2012 }}, including the match against Portugal on 26 April 1989: ''RSSSF'' website.</ref>\n\nOriginally he was due to retire at the end of the [[1990-91 in English football|1990\u201391]] season. However, in common with a number of high-performing referees at that time, he was granted an extension. This gave him a few more months at FIFA level before the world body reduced its own retirement age to 45 and, along with many other referees, he had to stand down at the end of 1991. However, he continued to referee in England. He was chosen for the new [[Premier League]] in 1992, and in 1993 took charge of the [[1993 Football League Cup Final|League Cup Final]] between [[Arsenal FC|Arsenal]] and [[Sheffield Wednesday FC|Sheffield Wednesday]].<ref>[http://www.soccerbase.com/results3.sd?gameid=260059 Coca Cola Cup Final 1993]: soccerbase.com website.</ref>\n\nHe was then granted a further domestic extension. Early in 1994, though, he decided to retire at the end of the season at the age of 51, after a 17-year career on the full List. He accepted an offer from [[The Football Association|the FA]] in 2000 to become a member of the video panel reviewing match events and disciplinary matters.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/896175.stm \"Busy start for FA video panel\"], which included Allan Gunn from 2000: [[BBC.co.uk]] website article.</ref> He died in 2004.\n\n==References==\n\n===Print===\n{{refbegin}}\n*Football League Handbooks, 1974\u20131976\n*Rothmans Football Yearbooks, 1977\u20131994\n*Gilbert Upton (2005) Football League and Premiership Referees 1888 to 2005: a Reference Resource, Soccerdata\n{{refend}}\n\n===Internet===\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.soccerbase.com/refs2.sd?refid=6 Allan Gunn Referee Statistics] at [[soccerbase]].com (1992-93 only)\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|title=[[FA Cup Final|FA&nbsp;Cup&nbsp;Final]]&nbsp;Referee|before=[[Joe Worrall (referee)|Joe Worrall]] |after=[[Roger Milford]] ||years=[[FA Cup Final 1990|1990]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gunn, Allan}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:People from Burgess Hill]]\n[[Category:Whitehawk F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English football referees]]\n[[Category:FA Cup Final referees]]\n[[Category:2004 deaths]]\n[[Category:English Football League referees]]\n[[Category:Premier League referees]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "add referee link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allan_Gunn"}
{"title_page": "Coin Master", "text_new": "{{Infobox game\n| name = Coin Master\n| image = \n| caption = \n| years = \n| genre = [[Casual game|Casual mobile game]]\n| players = [[Single-player]]\n| setup_time = \n| playing_time = \n| random_chance = \n| skills = \n}}\n'''Coin Master''' is a free, [[single-player]], [[Casual game|casual mobile game]] created by Israeli<ref>https://www.linkedin.com/organization-guest/company/moon-active</ref> studio Moon Active.<ref>{{cite news |title=Top trending game of the week on Android smartphones - Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/gadgets-news/top-trending-game-of-the-week-on-android-smartphones/articleshow/71690865.cms |work=The Times of India}}</ref> It was released in 2016 and earned its reputation as one of the most interactive mobile games on the market.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coin Master net revenue grows 833% year-on-year as Moon Active steps up its monetisation game |url=https://technology.ihs.com/615860/coin-master-net-revenue-grows-833-year-on-year-as-moon-active-steps-up-its-monetisation-game |work=[[IHS Markit]]}}</ref> It has had over 81 million downloads (as of October 2019). Coin Master is the top-grossing mobile game in the UK (since February 2019) and Germany (since June 2019).<ref>{{cite news |title=Coin Master Rakes in $500 Million Globally as It Cashes in On Success in Great Britain, Germany, and the U.S. |url=https://sensortower.com/blog/coin-master-revenue-500-million |work=Sensortower.com}}</ref>\n\n==Gameplay==\nThe objective of Coin Master is to win coins to upgrade items in order to build up villages.<ref name=gameplay>{{cite web |title=Gameplay |url=https://moonactive.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/sections/360000924273-Gameplay}}</ref><ref name=koaltion>{{cite web |title=App Trend Games of 2019: Coin Master Tops Charts |url=https://thekoalition.com/2019/app-trend-games-of-2019-coin-master-tops-charts |date=December 29, 2019  |website=thekoalition.com |publisher=Koalition}}</ref>\n\nCoin Master can be found under the 'Adventure Game' category in the [[app stores]], but uses [[game mechanics]]. In order to build their own game villages or attack the villages of other players, users must spin to win coins. The number of attempts is limited to six per hour, but additional attempts and items can be purchased in chests.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spiegel.de/plus/gaming-app-coin-master-wie-kinder-in-der-spielgeldfalle-landen-a-00000000-0002-0001-0000-000165335755|title=Gaming-App Coin Master: Wie Kinder in der Spielgeldfalle landen|work=Spiegel Online}}</ref>\n\n===Strategy===\nA fortune is acquired by spinning and winning, attacking another player's village or raiding another player\u2019s fortune. A maximum of five shields, as well as the pet Rhino, can be to defend villages. When a player's village is attacked, the game also allows a \"revenge\" allowing the player to launch a counterattack.<ref name=gameplay/>\n\n===Levels===\nPlayers advance to the next village once theirs is built, and they continuously get more challenging as the player progresses.<ref name=iLounge/> As of April 2020, Coin Master has 252 levels.<ref name=villages>{{cite web |title=Villages |url=https://moonactive.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/articles/360011318100-Villages |access-date=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Villages===\nPlayers continue to spin, win and build through over 200 uniquely themed village adventures, such as LA dreams, Buddhist village, Hell's village, and so on. Other village themes include Magical Forest, Steampunk Land, and Coin Manor.<ref name=iLounge>{{cite web |title=Coin Master: How The App Lives Up To Its Name |url=https://www.ilounge.com/articles/coin-master-how-the-app-lives-up-to-its-name |date=January 2, 2020 |website=ilounge.com |publisher=iLounge}}</ref><ref name=gazettereview>{{cite web |title=Coin Master: How The App Lives Up To Its Name |url=https://gazettereview.com/2019/12/coin-master-taken-casual-gaming-storm-lets-take-look-successful/ |website=gazettereview.com |publisher=Gazette Review}}</ref> Villages have five items, which can include characters, pets, homes, transportation, and items from nature.<ref name=koaltion/>\n\n===Card collection===\nAn extremely popular feature in the game is the \u2018Card Collection\u2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coin Master Has Taken Casual Gaming by Storm: Let\u2019s Take a Look at Why It\u2019s Been So Successful |url=https://www.techshout.com/games/2019/29/coin-master-by-moon-active-how-this-game-became-a-sensation-in-2019/ |website=gazettereview.com |publisher=TechShout}}</ref> Players make tremendous efforts to collect and trade cards in hopes of completing card set ts, which are used to win sought-after rewards such as spins, pet experience and more. Chests with collectible cards inside them can also be collected using coins.<ref name=gamenguide/>\n\nCards differ in value, and some of the rarest ones can be very difficult to find. The most precious cards can be shown off to the player's communities.<ref name=gazettereview/>\n\nThere are countless online social groups of fans from all over the world that are dedicated purely to card trading.<ref name=gamenguide>{{cite web |title=Predicting the Next Social Game Sensation: How Coin Master Took Us By Surprise |url=https://www.gamenguide.com/articles/101074/20191230/predicting-the-next-social-game-sensation-how-coin-master-took-us-by-surprise.htm |date=January 2, 2020 |website=gamenguide.com}}</ref>\n\n===Characters===\nThe pig that is placed in all the events and promotion art of the game is the protagonist (tour guide) of Coin Master.\n\nAdditionally, there are new characters introduced in every village.<ref>{{cite web |title=5 Coin Master Tips & Tricks You Need to Know |url=https://heavy.com/games/2019/03/coin-master-game-tips-guide/ |website=heavy.com |publisher=Heavy}}</ref>\n\nThe game also features other mythological characters such as wizards, witches, warriors, and queens.<ref name=gazettereview/>\n\n===Pets===\nFoxy, Tiger, and Rhino are the 3 pets that are designed to help players collect more coins each in their own unique way. Pets can be raised by obtaining treats for them and raising their XP ([[experience point]]s) by using XP potions. Pets can also have eggs that can be hatched. Additionally, pets need to be kept awake with treats. They can stay awake for longer periods of time with multiple treats.<ref name=gameplay/>\n\n==Commercial==\nAs of October 2019, Coin Master has grossed over $508 million in gross revenue. 85% of Coin Master's net revenue comes from the U.S, the UK and Germany combined - over $260 million from the United States, a dramatic jump in the UK (since February 2019) resulting in $80 million, and Germany close behind with $52 million. Coin Master surpassed [[Candy Crush Saga]] as top-grossing game and claimed first place on both the App Store and Google Play store in the United Kingdom and Ireland.<ref>{{cite news |title=These are the iPhone's most popular apps |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/iphone-best-apps-2019-apple-app-store-most-popular-a9230706.html |work=The Independent |date=3 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Forde |first1=Matthew |title=Weekly global mobile games charts: Coin Master overtakes Candy Crush Saga in Great Britain and Ireland for top grossing |url=https://www.pocketgamer.biz/asia/news/70042/weekly-global-mobile-games-charts-coin-master-overtakes-candy-crush-saga-in-great-britain-and-ireland-for-top-grossing/ |work=[[Pocket Gamer]]}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the website [[OMR Festival|OMR]], Moon Active earned $US 280 million until October 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://omr.com/de/coin-master-app-umsatz-influencer/|title=Coin Master: So hat die Gl\u00fccksspiel-App durch Influencer 280 Millionen Dollar umgesetzt|date=July 30, 2019|website=Daily}}</ref>\n\nIn his [[Neo Magazin Royale|late night show]] on [[Zweites Deutsches Fernsehen|German public TV]], [[Jan B\u00f6hmermann]] voiced his opinion that Coin Master is marketed to children and adolescents despite corresponding denials, among other things such as the child-friendly look of the game and advertising from popular influencers like [[Pietro Lombardi (singer)|Pietro Lombardi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.derstandard.at/story/2000109767814/jan-boehmermann-nimmt-sich-gluecksspielaehnliche-app-coinmaster-vor|title=B\u00f6hmermann nimmt sich gl\u00fccksspiel\u00e4hnliche App \"Coin Master\" vor - derStandard.de|website=Der Standard}}</ref>\n\n==Investors==\nThe company has investors from the [[tech industry]], such as [[Gigi Levy-Weiss]], the former CEO of the [[Gibraltar]]-based [[online casino]] company [[888 Holdings]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Indizierungsverfahren zu der App \u201eCoin Master\u201c eingeleitet |url=https://www.mimikama.at/allgemein/indizierungsverfahren-zu-der-app-coin-master-eingeleitet/ |work=Mimikama |date=16 October 2019 |language=de-DE}}</ref>\n\n==Advertisements==\n[[Jennifer Lopez]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://theblast.com/112238/jennifer-lopez-playing-coin-master-in-a-grocery-store-hits-1-mil |title=Jennifer Lopez Playing Coin Master In A Grocery Store Hits 1 Million Views |date=February 12, 2020 |website=theblast.com |publisher=The Blast}}</ref> [[Khlo\u00e9 Kardashian]], [[Kris Jenner]], and [[Scott Disick]] have also tried out Coin Master and endorsed it.<ref name=broadwayworld>{{cite web |title=Khlo\u00e9 Kardashian, Kris Jenner and Scott Disick Go on the Attack in Coin Master Campaign |url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/Khlo-Kardashian-Kris-Jenner-and-Scott-Disick-Go-on-the-Attack-in-COIN-MASTER-Campaign-20200117 |date=January 17, 2020 |website=broadwayworld.com |publisher=Broadway World}}</ref><ref name=people>{{cite web |title=Watch Kris Jenner Use Her Momager Negotiating Skills with Scott Disick in Funny Coin Master Ad |url=https://people.com/tv/kris-jenner-uses-her-momager-negotiating-skills-with-scott-disick/ |first=Natalie |last=Stone |date=January 23, 2020 |website=people.com |publisher=People}}</ref><ref name=gamerant>{{cite web |title=The Kardashians Are The Latest Celebrities to Endorse This Mobile Game |url=https://gamerant.com/kardashian-coin-master-mobile-game/ |first=Ramon |last=Hara |date=January 20, 2020 |website=gamerant.com |publisher=Gamerant}}</ref> Other celebrities who have endorsed Coin Master are [[Ben Higgins]] and [[Chris Harrison]].<ref name=accept>{{cite web |title=Ben Higgins and Chris Harrison tackle mobile game \u201cCoin Master\u201d |url=https://acceptthisrose.com/2020/01/21/ben-higgins-chris-harrison-tackle-mobile-game-coin-master/amp/ |first=Ariba |last=Bhuvad |website=acceptthisrose.com |publisher=FanSided}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nCoin Master was ranked in the ''top 20 of the acclaimed Top 50 Developers/Top 50 Mobile Game Makers'' list from [[Pocket Gamer|PocketGamer.biz]], published October 1st, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Top 50 Mobile Game Makers of 2019 |url=https://www.pocketgamer.biz/list/71427/the-top-50-mobile-game-makers-of-2019/entry/14/ |website=pocketgamer.biz |publisher=PocketGamer}}</ref> The game has also received countless mentions in industry publications regarding its continuous stance of 1st place in the weekly/monthly roundup lists of Top Grossing games on both the App Store and Google Play in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Forde |first1=Matthew |title=Weekly global mobile games charts: Coin Master overtakes Candy Crush Saga in Great Britain and Ireland for top grossing |url=https://www.pocketgamer.biz/asia/news/70042/weekly-global-mobile-games-charts-coin-master-overtakes-candy-crush-saga-in-great-britain-and-ireland-for-top-grossing/ |website=Pocketgamer.biz}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n[https://cmadroit.com/coin-master-chests/ Coin Master Chest Lists And Rewards]\n\n==External Links==\n* [https://www.moonactive.com Coin Master at MoonActive]\n\n[[Category:Active massively multiplayer online games]]\n[[Category:Social casual games]]\n[[Category:Free online games]]\n[[Category:Free-to-play video games]]\n[[Category:iOS games]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Windows Phone games]]\n[[Category:MacOS games]]\n[[Category:Massively multiplayer online role-playing games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Israel]]\n[[Category:2016 video games]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox game\n| name = Coin Master\n| image = \n| caption = \n| years = \n| genre = [[Casual game|Casual mobile game]]\n| players = [[Single-player]]\n| setup_time = \n| playing_time = \n| random_chance = \n| skills = \n}}\n'''Coin Master''' is a free, [[single-player]], [[Casual game|casual mobile game]] created by Israeli<ref>https://www.linkedin.com/organization-guest/company/moon-active</ref> studio Moon Active.<ref>{{cite news |title=Top trending game of the week on Android smartphones - Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/gadgets-news/top-trending-game-of-the-week-on-android-smartphones/articleshow/71690865.cms |work=The Times of India}}</ref> It was released in 2016 and earned its reputation as one of the most interactive mobile games on the market.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coin Master net revenue grows 833% year-on-year as Moon Active steps up its monetisation game |url=https://technology.ihs.com/615860/coin-master-net-revenue-grows-833-year-on-year-as-moon-active-steps-up-its-monetisation-game |work=[[IHS Markit]]}}</ref> It has had over 81 million downloads (as of October 2019). Coin Master is the top-grossing mobile game in the UK (since February 2019) and Germany (since June 2019).<ref>{{cite news |title=Coin Master Rakes in $500 Million Globally as It Cashes in On Success in Great Britain, Germany, and the U.S. |url=https://sensortower.com/blog/coin-master-revenue-500-million |work=Sensortower.com}}</ref>\n\n==Gameplay==\nThe objective of Coin Master is to win coins to upgrade items in order to build up villages.<ref name=gameplay>{{cite web |t