:England under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:England international footballers]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1996 players]]\n[[Category:1998 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 2000 players]]\n[[Category:English association football commentators]]\n[[Category:Major League Soccer broadcasters]]\n[[Category:English expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:English expatriate sportspeople in Spain]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Spain]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGal\u00e1cticos policy:Remove leading zero from dates", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steve_McManaman"}
{"title_page": "Salisbury rail crash", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox public transit accident\n| name                = Salisbury rail crash\n<!-- Image          -->\n| image               = Railway Disaster at Salisbury, 1st July, 1906.png\n| image_size          = \n| image_alt           = \n| caption             = \n<!-- Maps           -->\n| image_map           = \n| image_map_alt       = \n| image_map_caption   = \n| pushpin_map         = \n| alternative_map     = \n| pushpin_map_alt     = \n| pushpin_map_caption = \n| mapframe            = \n| qid                 = \n| mapframe_zoom       = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|51.0708|-1.8042|region:GB-DGY_type:landmark_scale:50000|display=inline,title}}\n<!-- Details        -->\n| date                = 1 July 1906| time                = 1:57&nbsp;am\n| location            = [[Salisbury railway station]], Wiltshire\n| location_dir        = \n| location_city       = \n| location_dist_km    = \n| location_dist_mi    = \n| country             = England\n| line                = [[West of England Main Line]]\n| operator            = [[London and South Western Railway]]\n| owner               = \n| service             = \n| cause               = Overspeed on curve\n<!-- Statistics     --> \n| bus                 = \n| trains              = 3\n| vehicles            = \n| passengers          = 43\n| crew                = \n| pedestrians         = \n| deaths              = 28\n| injuries            = 11\n| damage              = \n| property            = \n<!-- Route map      -->\n| route_map           = \n| route_map_state     = \n| route_map_name      = \n<!-- Footnotes      --> \n| footnotes           = [[List of rail accidents in the United Kingdom|List of UK rail accidents by year]]\n}}\nIn the '''Salisbury rail crash''' of 1 July 1906, a LSWR [[boat train]] from [[Plymouth Friary railway station|Plymouth]]'s Friary railway station to [[London Waterloo station]] failed to navigate a very sharp curve at the eastern end of [[Salisbury railway station]].  The curve had a [[Slow zone#Speed restrictions in the United Kingdom|maximum permitted speed]] of {{convert|30|mph|kph}}, but the express had been travelling at more than {{convert|70|mph|kph}}.  The train was completely [[derail]]ed, and smashed into a [[milk train]] and a light engine, killing 28 people.\n\n== Overview ==\nThe accident occurred at the same time as a short cut of the rival [[Great Western Railway]] was opening, and it was claimed that the driver of the crashed train was trying to show that his railway was capable of competitive speeds.  It was also rumoured that passengers \u2013 mostly rich [[New York City|New Yorkers]] travelling to London from the transatlantic port at Plymouth \u2013 had bribed the driver to run the train as fast as possible, but there was not any evidence of this, and if anything the train had lost time earlier.  Conversely, it was stated that drivers often ran through Salisbury very fast on these trains to \"get a run\" at the following hill.  The engine was a new [[LSWR L12 class]] 4-4-0 with a higher [[centre of gravity]] than the earlier [[LSWR T9 class|T9 class]].  The most likely cause of the accident is that the driver simply did not realise the level of risk he was running, particularly as this was the first occasion on which he had taken a non-stopping train through Salisbury.  Also, [[steam locomotives]] at this time, and for half a century afterwards, were not fitted with [[speedometer]]s.\n\nAs a result of the crash, all trains were required to stop at Salisbury station from that point onwards (the boat train at the time had no passenger stops from Plymouth to London Waterloo, although locomotives were changed at [[Templecombe railway station|Templecombe]]).<ref>{{cite book |title=British Railway Disasters |publisher=Ian Allan Ltd. |year=1996}}</ref> The speed limit on the curve east of Salisbury was also reduced to {{convert|15|mph|kph}}, a limit still in effect today.\n\nThere is a memorial tablet to the 28 dead (including the driver, two firemen and the guard) in Salisbury Cathedral.\n\nThe accident was the second in a series of three derailments due to excessive speed at night in a 16-month period. The others were at [[Grantham rail accident|Grantham]] 1906 and [[Shrewsbury rail accident|Shrewsbury]] 1907. All three resulted in deaths, including the footplate crews; the cause in each case was recorded as Driver Error but there has been much speculation since.\n\nIn 2006, historian Frogg Moody organised a memorial service at Salisbury Railway Station.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Lists of rail accidents]]\n* [[List of British rail accidents]]\n\n=== Similar accidents ===\n*  [[Amagasaki rail crash]] \u2013 2005 \u2013 Overspeed through sharp curve.\n*  [[Santiago de Compostela derailment]] \u2013 2013\n*  [[Eckwersheim derailment]] \u2013 2015 \n*  [[Rail accidents at Morpeth|Morpeth Railway Station]] \u2013 1877,1969,1984 \u2013 three occasions, overspeed through sharp curve.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book | first=J.A.B. | last=Hamilton. | title=British Railway Accidents of the 20th Century (reprinted as Tracks to Disaster). }}\n* {{cite book | first=O.S. | last=Nock |authorlink=O. S. Nock |year=1980 | title=Historic Railway Disasters | edition=2nd | publisher= Ian Allan Ltd}}\n* {{cite book |last= Pattenden |first= Norman |title= Salisbury 1906 \u2013 An answer to the enigma? |year= 2001 |publisher= South Western Circle |location= Swindon |isbn= 0-9503741-6-4 }}\n* {{cite book | first=L.T.C. | last=Rolt| year=1956 | title=Red for Danger | publisher= Bodley Head / David and Charles / Pan Books }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://danger-ahead.railfan.net/accidents/salisbry.htm Salisbury (1906) \u2013 description of the crash on the Danger Ahead website]\n* [http://www.railwaysarchive.co.uk/documents/BoT_Salisbury1906.pdf Official Board of Trade report (1906) at railwaysarchive.co.uk]\n\n{{Railway accidents in the United Kingdom, 1900\u20131999|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Derailments in England]]\n[[Category:Rail transport in Wiltshire]]\n[[Category:History of Salisbury]]\n[[Category:Railway accidents in 1906]]\n[[Category:1906 in England]]\n[[Category:20th century in Wiltshire]]\n[[Category:Accidents and incidents involving London and South Western Railway]]\n[[Category:July 1906 events]]\n[[Category:Train collisions in England]]\n[[Category:Rail accidents caused by a driver's error]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox public transit accident\n| name                = Salisbury rail crash\n<!-- Image          -->\n| image               = Railway Disaster at Salisbury, 1st July, 1906.png\n| image_size          = \n| image_alt           = \n| caption             = \n<!-- Maps           -->\n| image_map           = \n| image_map_alt       = \n| image_map_caption   = \n| pushpin_map         = \n| alternative_map     = \n| pushpin_map_alt     = \n| pushpin_map_caption = \n| mapframe            = \n| qid                 = \n| mapframe_zoom       = \n| coordinates         = {{coord|51.0708|-1.8042|region:GB-DGY_type:landmark_scale:50000|display=inline,title}}\n<!-- Details        -->\n| date                = 1 July 1906| time                = 1:57&nbsp;am\n| location            = [[Salisbury railway station]], Wiltshire\n| location_dir        = \n| location_city       = \n| location_dist_km    = \n| location_dist_mi    = \n| country             = England\n| line                = [[West of England Main Line]]\n| operator            = [[London and South Western Railway]]\n| owner               = \n| service             = \n| cause               = Overspeed on curve\n<!-- Statistics     --> \n| bus                 = \n| trains              = 3\n| vehicles            = \n| passengers          = 43\n| crew                = \n| pedestrians         = \n| deaths              = 28\n| injuries            = 11\n| damage              = \n| property            = \n<!-- Route map      -->\n| route_map           = \n| route_map_state     = \n| route_map_name      = \n<!-- Footnotes      --> \n| footnotes           = [[List of rail accidents in the United Kingdom|List of UK rail accidents by year]]\n}}\nIn the '''Salisbury rail crash''' of 1 July 1906, a LSWR [[boat train]] from [[Plymouth Friary railway station|Plymouth]]'s Friary railway station to [[London Waterloo station]] failed to navigate a very sharp curve at the eastern end of [[Salisbury railway station]].  The curve had a [[Slow zone#Speed restrictions in the United Kingdom|maximum permitted speed]] of {{convert|30|mph|kph}}, but the express had been travelling at more than {{convert|70|mph|kph}}.  The train was completely [[derail]]ed, and smashed into a [[milk train]] and a light engine, killing 28 people.\n\n== Overview ==\nThe accident occurred at the same time as a short cut of the rival [[Great Western Railway]] was opening, and it was claimed that the driver of the crashed train was trying to show that his railway was capable of competitive speeds.  It was also rumoured that passengers \u2013 mostly rich [[New York City|New Yorkers]] travelling to London from the transatlantic port at Plymouth \u2013 had bribed the driver to run the train as fast as possible, but there was not any evidence of this, and if anything the train had lost time earlier.  Conversely, it was stated that drivers often ran through Salisbury very fast on these trains to \"get a run\" at the following hill.  The engine was a new [[LSWR L12 class]] 4-4-0 with a higher [[centre of gravity]] than the earlier [[LSWR T9 class|T9 class]].  The most likely cause of the accident is that the driver simply did not realise the level of risk he was running, particularly as this was the first occasion on which he had taken a non-stopping train through Salisbury.  Also, [[steam locomotives]] at this time, and for half a century afterwards, were not fitted with [[speedometer]]s.\n\nAs a result of the crash, all trains were required to stop at Salisbury station from that point onwards (the boat train at the time had no passenger stops from Plymouth to London Waterloo, although locomotives were changed at [[Templecombe railway station|Templecombe]]).<ref>{{cite book |title=British Railway Disasters |publisher=Ian Allan Ltd. |year=1996}}</ref> The speed limit on the curve east of Salisbury was also reduced to 15&nbsp;mph, a limit still in effect today.\n\nThere is a memorial tablet to the 28 dead (including the driver, two firemen and the guard) in Salisbury Cathedral.\n\nThe accident was the second in a series of three derailments due to excessive speed at night in a 16-month period. The others were at [[Grantham rail accident|Grantham]] 1906 and [[Shrewsbury rail accident|Shrewsbury]] 1907. All three resulted in deaths, including the footplate crews; the cause in each case was recorded as Driver Error but there has been much speculation since.\n\nIn 2006, historian Frogg Moody organised a memorial service at Salisbury Railway Station.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Lists of rail accidents]]\n* [[List of British rail accidents]]\n\n=== Similar accidents ===\n*  [[Amagasaki rail crash]] \u2013 2005 \u2013 Overspeed through sharp curve.\n*  [[Rail accidents at Morpeth|Morpeth Railway Station]] \u2013 three occasions, overspeed through sharp curve.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book | first=J.A.B. | last=Hamilton. | title=British Railway Accidents of the 20th Century (reprinted as Tracks to Disaster). }}\n* {{cite book | first=O.S. | last=Nock |authorlink=O. S. Nock |year=1980 | title=Historic Railway Disasters | edition=2nd | publisher= Ian Allan Ltd}}\n* {{cite book |last= Pattenden |first= Norman |title= Salisbury 1906 \u2013 An answer to the enigma? |year= 2001 |publisher= South Western Circle |location= Swindon |isbn= 0-9503741-6-4 }}\n* {{cite book 